            <p><note type="lingcomment">The commentary is adapted from <bibl><title corresp="ref:jietal1998"/><citedRange>108</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note type="parallels">MaitrHami 2, 8-10</note><note type="remarks">This fragment contains part of the second act of the Maitreyasamitināṭaka; an Uy. parallel is MaitrHami II, 8b27-10a5. See also <bibl><title corresp="ref:pinault1999"/><citedRange>195-6</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note type="remarks">The translation and the following commentary are adapted from <bibl><title corresp="ref:jietal1998"/><citedRange>108</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="lingcomment"><hi>wināsamśi</hi> is a verse variant of <hi>wināsamäśśi</hi>, morphologically |wäynāsamäs-cäy| (<bibl><title corresp="ref:siegetal1931"/><citedRange>329</citedRange></bibl>).</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 8 b28ff., and the last line of this leaf corresponds to MaitrHami 2, 10 a5ff. (for the Uy. references cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:jietal1998"/><citedRange>18</citedRange></bibl>).</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 9 a2ff.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 9 a9ff.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 9 a15ff.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment"><hi>nandavilāpaṃ</hi>: two stanzas of 4 x 15 (7/8) syllables.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment"><hi>kārāśäntwä</hi>: this form is a mistake for <hi>kārāśäntu</hi> ('in the wilds and the woodlands') or, less likely, <hi>kārāśäntwaṃ</hi> ('in the wilds and in the woodlands'). The mistake is probably due to the next word, which starts with <hi>wä</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 9 b2ff.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="lingcomment">TA <hi>ṣāṣtru</hi> is the past participle of hitherto unattested <hi>ṣtār-</hi>; this verb stem is related to <hi>ṣtare</hi> ‘Anstrengung’ as <hi>mālk-</hi> is to <hi>malke</hi> ‘milk’ or <hi>swās-</hi> to <hi>swase</hi> ‘rain’.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 9 b17ff.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">The Uyghur text has the name Suyāma, borrowed in the form <hi>suyami</hi>, MaitrHami 2, 9 b21.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment"><hi>maitraṃ</hi>: two stanzas of 4 x 12 (5/7) syllables.</note><note corresp="#b7" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 10 a1f.</note><note corresp="#b8" type="lingcomment">TA <hi>ymatu</hi>, of uncertain meaning, recurs in a context of homage being expressed in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a62"/>: a1, <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a251"/>: b4, and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a252"/>: b4; cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegetal1931"/><citedRange>17</citedRange></bibl>.</note></p>
